{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641510"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:27:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:27:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17884"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17884","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17884"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.1,0.03,0.21,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10598"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115095"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10598"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17884"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97103"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5102"},{"type":"tags","id":"9878"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24701"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24705"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115095"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors increases glucagon secretion during fasting?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Somatostatin","Insulin","Glucose","Catecholamines","Cortisol"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring fasting, the body needs to maintain blood glucose levels, and one of the hormones involved in this process is glucagon. \u003Cstrong\u003ECatecholamines\u003C/strong\u003E, such as adrenaline, stimulate glucagon secretion, especially during stress or fasting, to increase blood glucose levels by promoting glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin\u003C/strong\u003E typically inhibits glucagon secretion. During fasting, insulin levels are low, which allows glucagon levels to rise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESomatostatin\u003C/strong\u003E is a hormone that inhibits the secretion of several other hormones, including glucagon. It acts as a regulatory hormone to balance the effects of glucagon and insulin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose\u003C/strong\u003E itself does not directly increase glucagon secretion. In fact, high glucose levels typically suppress glucagon release.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECortisol\u003C/strong\u003E is a glucocorticoid hormone that can influence glucose metabolism, but it does not directly increase glucagon secretion during fasting. Its primary role is in the longer-term regulation of metabolism and stress response.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Glucagon secretion is increased during fasting to maintain blood glucose levels.","Catecholamines stimulate glucagon secretion, especially during stress or fasting.","Insulin typically inhibits glucagon secretion."],"references":["Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. Boca Raton: CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a Glance. Hoboken: John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Chandel NS. Amino Acid Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Apr 1;13(4):a040584.","Ling ZN, Jiang YF, Ru JN, Lu JH, Ding B, Wu J. Amino acid metabolism in health and disease. Signal Transduct Target Ther. 2023 Sep 13;8(1):345.","Nakrani MN, Wineland RH, Anjum F. Physiology, Glucose Metabolism. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jul 17 [updated 2024 Jan].","Chandel NS. Carbohydrate Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Jan 4;13(1):a040568."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97103"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17884"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97103","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97103"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-22T11:13:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T11:13:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10598"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115095"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4929"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6d","name":"Endocrine","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:5